🧩 What Is Error Handling in Express?

Error handling means catching and managing mistakes that happen in your app — like a missing file, wrong URL, or a crash due to bad code — without breaking the whole server.
Express gives a special type of middleware for handling errors.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
🧱 1. Basic Error Handling (Beginner Level)
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Normal route
app.get('/', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Home Page');
});

// Route with error
app.get('/error', (req, res) => {
  throw new Error('Something went wrong!');
});

// Error handling middleware
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(500).send('Server Error Occurred!');
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server running on port 3000'));
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🧠 Explanation:

When /error route is visited, it throws an error.
Express automatically forwards it to the error-handling middleware.
The middleware has 4 parameters: (err, req, res, next) → always 4.
It catches the error, logs it, and sends a friendly message instead of crashing the app.
