2).⚙️ Custom Error Messages in Express.js

Custom error messages mean you decide what message to send when something goes wrong — instead of showing the default “Internal Server Error.”
It helps you explain clearly what the problem is (for example, “User not found” or “Invalid password”).

const express = require("express");
const app = express();

// Example route
app.get("/user/:id", (req, res, next) => {
  const userId = req.params.id;

  // Example: user not found
  if (userId !== "10") {
    const err = new Error("❌ User not found! Please check the ID.");
    err.status = 404; // custom HTTP status
    return next(err); // send error to middleware
  }

  res.send("✅ User found!");
});

// Custom Error Handler
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    success: false,
    message: err.message || "Something went wrong!",
  });
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log("Server running on port 3000"));

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🧾 Explanation (Step by Step):

new Error("User not found!") → create a custom message.
err.status = 404 → give a custom HTTP code.
next(err) → send this error to your error handler.
In the error handler, Express automatically sends back your custom message.

