4).⚙️ Centralized Error Handling (Middleware)(MAIN)


🧠 Definition (Easy Words)

Centralized Error Handling means — instead of writing try–catch everywhere in your code,
you make one special middleware that handles all errors from all routes in one place.
It helps keep your code clean and easy to maintain.
You just throw or pass the error using next(err) — and this one middleware handles everything.


const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Middleware to parse JSON
app.use(express.json());

// 🔹 Example Route 1 — throws error manually
app.get('/user', (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    throw new Error("User not found!");
  } catch (err) {
    next(err); // send to centralized error handler
  }
});

// 🔹 Example Route 2 — async route (like DB call)
app.get('/product', async (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    const product = null;
    if (!product) throw new Error("Product does not exist!");
    res.json(product);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err); // also goes to centralized handler
  }
});

// 🧱 CENTRALIZED ERROR HANDLER (must be at the end)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.log("Error caught:", err.message);

  res.status(500).json({
    success: false,
    message: err.message || "Something went wrong on the server!"
  });
});

// Start server
app.listen(3000, () => console.log("Server running on port 3000"));


